<bibRefCitation author="Sneli" box="[1303,1428,1068,1094]" firstAuthor="Sneli" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="229 - 259" refId="ref200983" refString="Sneli, J. - A. (1999) Echinodermata, Asteroidea in the Faroe region. Frodskaparrit, 47, 229 - 259." type="journal article" year="1999">Sneli 1999</bibRefCitation>
) south to 
<collectingCountry box="[247,348,1104,1130]" name="Morocco" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Morocco</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[362,548,1103,1130]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="178 - 187" refId="ref192529" refString="Mortensen, T. (1925) Echinodermes du Maroc et De Mauritanie. Bulletin de la Societe des sciences naturelles du Maroc, 5 (4 - 5), 178 - 187." type="journal article" year="1925">Mortensen 1925</bibRefCitation>
) and? 
<collectingCountry box="[620,751,1104,1130]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
(A.M. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark" box="[833,992,1104,1130]" firstAuthor="Clark" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="157 - 184" refId="ref176855" refString="Clark, A. M. (1982 a) Notes on Atlantic Asteroidea. 2. Luidiidae. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 42 (3), 157 - 184." type="journal article" year="1982" yearSuffix="a">Clark (1982a)</bibRefCitation>
, including the Azores, Madeira (
<bibRefCitation author="D ˆ derlein, L." journalOrPublisher="Siboga Expedition" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="193 - 291" part="46" refId="ref179071" refString="D ˆ derlein, L. (1920) Die Asteriden der Siboga-Expedition. 2. Die Gattung Luidia und ihre Stammesgeschichte. Siboga Expedition, 46, 193 - 291." title="Die Asteriden der Siboga-Expedition. 2. Die Gattung Luidia und ihre Stammesgeschichte" type="journal article" year="1920">D̂derlein 1920</bibRefCitation>
) and Canaries (
<bibRefCitation author="Madsen" box="[432,590,1139,1166]" firstAuthor="Madsen" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="167 - 222" refId="ref189080" refString="Madsen, F. J. (1950) The echinoderms collected by the Atlantide Expedition, 1945 - 46. 1. Asteroidea. Atlantide Reports, 1, 167 - 222." type="journal article" year="1950">Madsen 1950</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="79.[151,1437,995,1562]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,282,1176,1202]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Depth:</emphasis>
1–650(?805) m (A.M. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark" box="[538,677,1176,1202]" firstAuthor="Clark" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="157 - 184" refId="ref176855" refString="Clark, A. M. (1982 a) Notes on Atlantic Asteroidea. 2. Luidiidae. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 42 (3), 157 - 184." type="journal article" year="1982" yearSuffix="a">Clark 1982a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gage" box="[687,871,1176,1202]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Gage" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="263 - 308" refId="ref181395" refString="Gage, J. D., Billett, D. S. M., Jensen, M. &amp; Tyler, P. A. (1983) Echinoderms of the Rockall Trough and adjacent areas. I. Crinoidea, Asteroidea and Ophiuroidea. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 45, 263 - 308. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 28002" type="journal article" year="1983">
Gage 
<emphasis box="[751,799,1176,1202]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">et al</emphasis>
. 1983
</bibRefCitation>
), typically from 
<quantity box="[1054,1184,1175,1202]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.125" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.25" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" unit="m" value="112.5" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="25.0">25 to 200 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Madsen" box="[1197,1354,1175,1202]" firstAuthor="Madsen" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="167 - 222" refId="ref189080" refString="Madsen, F. J. (1950) The echinoderms collected by the Atlantide Expedition, 1945 - 46. 1. Asteroidea. Atlantide Reports, 1, 167 - 222." type="journal article" year="1950">Madsen 1950</bibRefCitation>
); 
<collectionCode box="[1371,1433,1176,1202]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">AZO</collectionCode>
:?littoral.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="79.[151,1437,995,1562]" box="[199,1122,1247,1274]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1247,1274]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Habitat:</emphasis>
hard to soft sediments, often found partly buried in gravel (
<bibRefCitation author="Picton" box="[969,1109,1248,1274]" firstAuthor="Picton" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" refId="ref197776" refString="Picton, B. (1993) A field guide to the shallow-water echinoderms of the British Isles. IMMEL Publishing Lda, London, 96 pp." type="book" year="1993">Picton 1993</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="79.[151,1437,995,1562]" box="[199,743,1284,1310]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,1284,1310]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Larval stage:</emphasis>
planktotrophic (
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[542,730,1284,1310]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" refId="ref192436" refString="Mortensen, T. (1921) Studies of the Development and Larval Forms of Echinoderms. G. E. C. Gad, Copenhagen, 294 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11376" type="book" year="1921">Mortensen 1921</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="79.[151,1437,995,1562]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1320,1346]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Remarks:</emphasis>
the first record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1927" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[524,683,1320,1346]" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paxillosida" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[524,683,1320,1346]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Luidia ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Azores can be trace back to 
<bibRefCitation author="D ˆ derlein, L." box="[1071,1283,1319,1346]" journalOrPublisher="Siboga Expedition" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="193 - 291" part="46" refId="ref179071" refString="D ˆ derlein, L. (1920) Die Asteriden der Siboga-Expedition. 2. Die Gattung Luidia und ihre Stammesgeschichte. Siboga Expedition, 46, 193 - 291." title="Die Asteriden der Siboga-Expedition. 2. Die Gattung Luidia und ihre Stammesgeschichte" type="journal article" year="1920">D̂derlein’s (1920)</bibRefCitation>
review of the genus, which included a specimen collected in the archipelago from the Simroth collection, though the later author never included any material belonging to this species or genus in his 1888’s report. More recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirtz" box="[1290,1436,1392,1418]" firstAuthor="Wirtz" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="45 - 49" refId="ref204543" refString="Wirtz, P. (2009) Ten new records of marine invertebrates from the Azores. Arquipelago, Life and Marine Sciences, 26, 45 - 49." type="journal article" year="2009">Wirtz (2009)</bibRefCitation>
reported an animal of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1927" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[405,566,1428,1454]" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paxillosida" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[405,566,1428,1454]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Luidia ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a large tide-pool at Faial Island (not collected). The latter author claimed that a picture could be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirtz &amp; Debelius" box="[506,787,1464,1490]" firstAuthor="Wirtz" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" refId="ref204573" refString="Wirtz, P. &amp; Debelius, H. (2003) Mediterranean and Atlantic invertebrate guide. ConchBooks, Hackenheim, 305 pp." type="book" year="2003">Wirtz &amp; Debelius (2003)</bibRefCitation>
, however, the photographed specimen in the 2003 work is from Madeira. The absence of documented specimens in the archipelago in over 80 years places the presence of this species in the Azores in a somewhat precarious position and thus, should be dealt with caution.
</paragraph>
